1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:19,720
One of the most important things that we need to address in any cryptography implementation

2
00:00:19,720 --> 00:00:39,800
is one of the most important things that we need to address in any cryptography implementation

3
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:41,560
is avoiding patterns.

4
00:00:41,560 --> 00:00:47,480
I think we've mentioned a few times how patterns is what kills cryptography and every single

5
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:54,040
example of where cryptography has failed has usually been because of some key management

6
00:00:54,040 --> 00:00:59,480
implementation issue of where patterns are evident and certainly throughout history

7
00:00:59,480 --> 00:01:01,520
we've seen that many times.

8
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:07,360
So it's important for organizations in how they implement cryptography solutions to avoid

9
00:01:07,360 --> 00:01:13,040
patterns and patterns are really bad and that's what we're going to try and show here

10
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:17,800
in this section and we'll talk about certain ways to avoid patterns.

11
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:19,520
Now here's an example.

12
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:21,880
You probably know the answer to this.

13
00:01:21,880 --> 00:01:27,720
If we're using English as an example, there are certain language statistics that people

14
00:01:27,720 --> 00:01:30,080
know of the English language.

15
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:35,040
For example, what's the most commonly used letter in the English alphabet and the answer

16
00:01:35,040 --> 00:01:40,640
to that is the letter E. Well, how could that help some crypt analyst figure it out?

17
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:44,720
For example, what a key is in a cryptography implementation.

18
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:51,000
Well, if they've got some cypher text in front of them, they could count all of the letters

19
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:57,120
and the one that appears the most often might be the letter E because that's the most commonly

20
00:01:57,120 --> 00:02:00,160
used letter in the English alphabet.

21
00:02:00,160 --> 00:02:01,440
Let's keep going here.

22
00:02:01,440 --> 00:02:07,680
The most commonly used three letter word in the English alphabet is the word the.

23
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:13,800
So if you see some cypher text in front of you, for example, and you see a three letter

24
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:19,640
word that has been encrypted, you might assume is the letter the and you would approach decrypting

25
00:02:19,640 --> 00:02:22,600
that message in that fashion.

26
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:28,840
What's the most commonly used four letter word in the English alphabet, the word that?

27
00:02:28,840 --> 00:02:35,720
And this is a really important one because the word that always starts and ends with the

28
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:36,720
same letter.

29
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:43,040
So if you see some cypher text where it's a four letter word that has been encrypted,

30
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,280
that starts and ends with the same letter, you can assume and be pretty sure that it

31
00:02:48,280 --> 00:02:49,920
is the word that.

32
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:52,480
So that provides patterns.

33
00:02:52,480 --> 00:02:59,920
This type of activity in trying to find what certain keys are is called frequency analysis.

34
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:05,960
And that simply means that people know language statistics about the language that, for example,

35
00:03:05,960 --> 00:03:09,120
something has been encrypted in.

36
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:15,200
And just to reiterate this problem that we have in how patterns should always be avoided

37
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:22,320
in anything related to cryptography, simple substitution and transposition ciphers do not

38
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:23,840
hide patterns.

39
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:27,400
And you'll remember we showed you this example before.

40
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:33,280
For example, when we encrypt the word gobbins, the word gobbins has two b's in it.

41
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:37,240
That provides patterns that may be useful to attackers.

42
00:03:37,240 --> 00:03:44,400
And if you use simple substitution and transposition ciphers, the resulting cypher text also provides

43
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:50,000
patterns that may provide opportunities for attackers to eventually figure out what

44
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:51,520
the key is.

45
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:58,360
So in order to defeat frequency analysis, which is all about understanding what certain

46
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:06,280
statistics and patterns that exist in certain languages are, we have to create our own languages

47
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:12,280
and alphabets that nobody knows any language statistics about.

48
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:14,800
Here's a perfect example.

49
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:22,000
In this case, we are creating four different alphabets that each start with a different letter.

50
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:28,200
And the idea is if we want to encrypt the word gobbins, when we do it using this with

51
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:33,040
a key that is down at the bottom, four, three, one, two.

52
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:38,560
The idea is the first letter we're going to encrypt is the letter G, but because the first

53
00:04:38,560 --> 00:04:43,480
key value is the number four, we use the fourth alphabet.

54
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:50,160
So if we intersect the G with the fourth alphabet, we come up with the cypher text letter

55
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:51,160
C.

56
00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:56,640
Now if we do the next one, the next key value is the number three.

57
00:04:56,680 --> 00:04:59,160
That means we use the third alphabet.

58
00:04:59,160 --> 00:05:04,680
The letter we need to encrypt is the letter U. So if we intersect the letter U with the

59
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:10,440
third alphabet, it comes up with the cypher text letter R.

60
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:17,480
Now here's where patterns that appeared in the plaintext actually disappear because

61
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:22,400
we've created alphabets that nobody knows any language statistics about.

62
00:05:22,440 --> 00:05:30,760
So the first B in the plaintext becomes the letter A as cypher text.

63
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:35,400
Now the next B will not produce the same A, for example.

64
00:05:35,400 --> 00:05:43,720
So we hide the patterns that existed in the plaintext by creating what are called polyalphabetic

65
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:44,800
cypheres.

66
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:50,600
In this case, the second B creates a Z as the cypher text letter.

67
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:53,440
So patterns are actually hidden.

68
00:05:53,440 --> 00:05:59,400
So what you want to remember about polyalphabetic cypheres, the word poly means many.

69
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:05,480
So you're creating many alphabets that overall are going to defeat any sort of frequency

70
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:10,440
analysis capabilities that monoalphabetic cypheres do not.

71
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:16,000
And a perfect example of this, if we keep going here, you're going to see that we're

72
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:22,720
going to create some very good cypher text that ultimately hides any patterns that may

73
00:06:22,720 --> 00:06:25,280
have existed in the plaintext itself.

74
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:30,640
Now, a really good example of something that's been used throughout history to be able to

75
00:06:30,640 --> 00:06:35,240
hide patterns is something called the running key cypher.

76
00:06:35,240 --> 00:06:42,240
And we have examples of this being used during that period after the Second World War when

77
00:06:42,240 --> 00:06:46,440
a lot of the countries didn't trust each other because of what happened at the end of

78
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:48,040
the Second World War.

79
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:53,520
So what happened in these cases, a lot of countries placed spies in other countries.

80
00:06:53,520 --> 00:06:58,200
But the way that these spies would communicate back with their home country would have been

81
00:06:58,200 --> 00:07:01,040
using what's called the running key cypher.

82
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:05,840
And the reason it's called running key cypher is because it requires the same book to

83
00:07:05,840 --> 00:07:08,040
exist at both ends.

84
00:07:08,040 --> 00:07:13,080
So let's say I'm the spy that's been placed in the Soviet Union.

85
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:18,240
And I'm trying to communicate back with the country here in the US, for example.

86
00:07:18,240 --> 00:07:24,800
And so what I do is I take the message that I want to encrypt and I combine it with text

87
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:28,600
that appears in a specific part of a book.

88
00:07:28,600 --> 00:07:35,280
So you and I would know that we are starting at page number 32, paragraph one, sentence

89
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:36,280
number one.

90
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:42,480
Whatever text that is becomes the key that I combine the secret message that I want

91
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:44,440
to communicate with you.

92
00:07:44,440 --> 00:07:51,120
And so the way that we combine is using the numeric equivalents of each of the letters

93
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:54,080
using what you see up on your screen there.

94
00:07:54,080 --> 00:08:00,840
So if we are encrypting the word gobbins as well and that text that appears on that page

95
00:08:00,840 --> 00:08:05,160
starts with the quick brown fox and so on.

96
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:10,120
What I do is I take the first letter of the secret message and I combine it with the first

97
00:08:10,120 --> 00:08:15,840
letter of the text that appears on that page, which in this case is the T. And if you combine

98
00:08:15,840 --> 00:08:19,280
the two, it comes up with that, right?

99
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:24,320
Obviously the number G is the seventh letter in the alphabet.

100
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:28,000
The T is the 20th letter in the alphabet.

101
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:33,920
So if we add the two, 20 plus seven is 27, that's more letters than we have in the English

102
00:08:33,920 --> 00:08:34,920
alphabet.

103
00:08:34,920 --> 00:08:38,520
So we have to subtract 26, which equals one.

104
00:08:38,520 --> 00:08:44,720
So your first cipher text letter is the first letter in the alphabet, which is the A.

105
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:49,680
And so if you keep going, the idea is you're going to come up with text.

106
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:54,120
When you receive that secret message at your end, you're going to have to know where

107
00:08:54,120 --> 00:08:56,000
we started in the book.

108
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:00,800
You're going to take the encrypted message and you're going to subtract the letters that

109
00:09:00,800 --> 00:09:05,160
appear on page 32, paragraph one, seconds number one.

110
00:09:05,160 --> 00:09:10,560
And that'll allow you to retrieve the encrypted message and be able to read it.

111
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:17,040
The idea is the next time you and I communicate, we use the same book, but we use a different

112
00:09:17,040 --> 00:09:18,600
portion of the book.

113
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:24,880
The idea is we've got endless possibilities of keys that we can use in order to encrypt

114
00:09:24,880 --> 00:09:25,880
messages.

115
00:09:25,880 --> 00:09:32,160
There's the really important point and that is we never reuse the same key.

116
00:09:32,160 --> 00:09:36,920
And so every single message will have a different key associated with it.

117
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:40,840
And that's why these sometimes were referred to as code books.

118
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:46,560
The idea is before I get to the Soviet Union, I would have a code book just like the one

119
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:48,560
you see on the screen here.

120
00:09:48,560 --> 00:09:55,200
And we would use a specific page and then once one page was used, it would be destroyed.

121
00:09:55,200 --> 00:09:59,720
And then the next time you and I communicated, we would use a different part of that code

122
00:09:59,720 --> 00:10:04,320
book, which ensures security of each message.

123
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:11,600
Now the problem with using a different key for every single message is what we call key

124
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:13,000
distribution.

125
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:17,440
But this, the running key cipher that we just described where we use the same book at

126
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:23,000
both ends, but a different part of the book for every single message is ensuring that

127
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,400
we have a different key for every single message.

128
00:10:26,400 --> 00:10:32,600
And this in cryptography actually has a specific term associated with it.

129
00:10:32,600 --> 00:10:35,920
It is known as a one time pad.

130
00:10:35,920 --> 00:10:42,640
So a one time pad means that for every single message that you encrypt, the key is changed

131
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:44,600
and it's never reused.

132
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:52,000
And in fact, the key is always the exact same length as the message that you're encrypting.

133
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:56,320
Because of that, the key is never reused and it's always the same length.

134
00:10:56,320 --> 00:11:03,240
It becomes the only unbreakable algorithm that exists where the key is only used one

135
00:11:03,240 --> 00:11:04,560
and never reused.

